Dave,

I think your view is close to the mark.  The hierarchical name structure
naturally wants to follow the delegation of control for chunks,
subchunks, ... of the name space.  Right now, we are usually able to make
the one name space conform to both control and organizational structure,
although there are some exceptions, such as in-addr.arpa, which wants to
be controlled along the lines of network allocation, not organizational
structure.

It gets ugly when we try to organize things according to two or more
different metrics.  (No name can serve two masters?)

The lesson here is that since control is a political issue, sooner or
later politics come to the fore in naming structures.  The EDU and GOV
domains are top level due to a political belief that such entities don't
necessarily need their country in their name; I have even heard it said
that GB is UK for a political reason.  I hasten to add that I don't
think either of these came out of smoke-filled rooms of the Trilateral
Commission or other evil body, they just fit the intuition of the people
making the rules at the time.

paul

